sec.p:
Each day includes four trading rounds (seefigure 1). The day opens with a round of trading between dealers and liquidity‐demanding customers, which is followed with a round of interdealer trading. After the first round of interdealer trading, order flow information is observed and there is a second round of interdealer trading. After the two interdealer trading rounds, there is a final round of customer‐dealer trade (this time with liquidity‐supplying customers) to share risk with the public more broadly. Indeed, the dealers end each day with no net risky position, leading them to maximize expected utility over intraday returns. Daily closing prices change due to the permanent inventory shifts of the liquidity‐demanding customers, on the one hand, and the willingness of the liquidity‐supplying customers to absorb them, on the other.
