               inequation (5)reflects that
                  \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $T_{i2t}^{^{\prime }}> 0$ \end{document}
               is a dealerisale in round 2).

The last event in round 2 defines the third of the model's three dimensions of transparency, that applying to interdealer trades. At the close of round 2, all dealers observe the round‐2 interdealer order flow:

               This sum over
                  \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $T_{i2t}$ \end{document}
               is net interdealer demand, the difference in buy and sell orders. In bond and FX markets,
                  \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $Z_{t}$ \end{document}
               is the information on interdealer order flow provided by interdealer brokers (see Lyons2001for details). Actual dealers in these markets describe this as an essential source of real‐time information.

Liquidity‐supplying (LS) customer trades in round 4 are nonstochastic: these agents are induced to trade conditional on past price movements and other information available to them. These trades are the means by which dealers share overnight risk with the nondealer public. Round 4 begins with each dealer quoting (simultaneously and independently) a scalar price
                  \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $P_{i4t}$ \end{document}
               at which he agrees to buy and sell any amount. These quotes are observable and available to all LS customers.

The mass of public investors on the interval [0,m] is large relative to thendealers. This implies that the dealers' capacity for bearing overnight risk is small relative to the public's capacity (despite dealers and public investors having the same coefficient of risk aversion). Nevertheless, the public is assumed to have risk‐bearing capacity that is finite. Under these assumptions, dealers will optimally set prices such that the public willingly absorbs dealer inventory imbalances, and each dealer ends the day with no net position.15These round‐4 prices are conditioned on the interdealer order flow
                  \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $Z_{t}$ \end{document}
               . The interdealer order flow informs dealers of the total size of the position that the public needs to absorb to bring the dealers back to a position of zero.

Each dealer determines quotes and speculative demand by maximizing the utility function shown inequation (1). Because dealers hold no overnight positions and dealers face a daily stochastic environment that is time invariant, the solution to the corresponding 1‐period problem is intertemporally optimal. Letting
